{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488418"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:41:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:41:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"437"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"437","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/437"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.03,0.07,0.46,0.39]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"437"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83007"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"437","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/437"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"437"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68067"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1158"},{"type":"tags","id":"2043"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2979"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2997"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28389"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44462"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45051"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83007"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with intermittent discharge from her right nipple. She has not experienced any similar symptoms in the past and does not report any pain, skin changes, or lumps in her breast. She has not experienced weight loss, night sweats, or fatigue lately.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe is otherwise well; her only medication is the oral contraceptive pill, which she started at the age of 16 for contraceptive reasons. She has never had any children and had her first period at the age of 14.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn breast examination, there is no asymmetry, no nipple inversion, and there are no palpable lumps in either breast; however, some material can be expressed from the nipple when gentle pressure is applied to the adjacent tissue (image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of the discharge?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Invasive ductal carcinoma","Breast abscess","Paget disease of the nipple","Duct ectasia","Intraductal papilloma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient most likely has an \u003Cstrong\u003Eintraductal papilloma\u003C/strong\u003E; a small tumour in the milk duct of the breast that produces discharge. The discharge associated with a duct papilloma tends to be serous or serosanguinous - as in this case. Furthermore, the lack of other more concerning signs, such as a palpable mass, constitutional symptoms, cancer risk factors, and young age make this diagnosis more likely than other, more serious and concerning differentials.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInvasive ductal carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common type of breast cancer, causing over 80% of breast cancers. Whilst this differential must be considered (further investigation including imaging and possibly pathology may be necessary to rule this out), it is not the most likely diagnosis given the lack of a breast mass, inflammatory skin changes, and constitutional symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBreast abscess\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to cause discharge from the nipple without other associated symptoms such as a breast mass, pain, and fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESimilarly, \u003Cstrong\u003EPaget\u0027s disease of the nipple\u003C/strong\u003E is an inflammatory condition that causes scaly, red, itchy irritation on the surface of the nipple. This patient has none of these changes, and thus, her discharge is not likely to be a result of Paget\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EClassically, \u003Cstrong\u003Educt ectasia\u003C/strong\u003E causes a green, yellow or even black discharge from the breast, is often bilateral and is occasionally associated with breast tenderness. It can cause an inverted nipple. It is less likely in this woman given the lack of tenderness and characteristic discharge that is almost always present in this condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A duct papilloma is a benign tumour of the milk duct of the breast that produces a serous or serosanguinous discharge.","Intraductal papilloma is a common cause of unilateral nipple discharge in premenopausal women.","Breast examination in cases of nipple discharge should include assessment for lumps, skin changes, and expression of discharge."],"references":["Li A, Kirk L. Intraductal Papilloma. 2022 Sep 26. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30137824. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30137824/","Abbassi-Rahbar S, Sack S, Larson KE, Wagner JL, Kilgore LJ, Balanoff CR, Winblad OD, Amin AL. Multidisciplinary Review of Intraductal Papilloma of the Breast can Identify Patients who may Omit Surgical Excision. Ann Surg Oncol. 2021 Oct;28(10):5768-5774. doi: 10.1245/s10434-021-10520-1. Epub 2021 Aug 2. PMID: 34338925. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34338925/","Li X, Wang H, Sun Z, Fan C, Jin F, Mao X. A retrospective observational study of intraductal breast papilloma and its coexisting lesions: A real-world experience. Cancer Med. 2020 Oct;9(20):7751-7762. doi: 10.1002/cam4.3308. Epub 2020 Aug 21. PMID: 32822113; PMCID: PMC7571817. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7571817/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68067"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"437"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15304"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15304","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15304"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/de874e8d-85cd-4785-a7ae-7f2b55f42c1b.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/de874e8d-85cd-4785-a7ae-7f2b55f42c1b.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":317,"height":315}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68067","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68067"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-31T21:29:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-31T21:29:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"437"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83007"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":n